text: To be fair, you have to have a very high IQ to understand Amy Schumer. The humour is extremely subtle, and without a solid grasp of theoretical physics most of the jokes will go over a typical viewer’s head. There’s Amy's nihilistic outlook, which is deftly woven into her characterisation- her personal philosophy draws heavily from Narodnaya Volya literature, for instance. The fans understand this stuff; they have the intellectual capacity to truly appreciate the depths of these jokes, to realise that they’re not just funny- they say something deep about LIFE. As a consequence people who dislike Amy Schumer truly ARE idiots- of course they wouldn’t appreciate, for instance, the humour in Amy's existential catchphrase “My Vagina!” which itself is a cryptic reference to Turgenev’s Russian epic Fathers and Sons. I’m smirking right now just imagining one of those addlepated simpletons scratching their heads in confusion as Amy Schumer's genius wit unfolds itself on the screen. What fools.. how I pity them. 😂  And yes, by the way, i DO have a Amy Schumer tattoo. And no, you cannot see it. It’s for the ladies’ eyes only- and even then they have to demonstrate that they’re within 5 IQ points of my own (preferably lower) beforehand. Nothin personnel kid 😎

Both smoking and obesity are incredibly dangerous lifestyles to live, but nobody is encouraging people to continue smoking and to accept people as smokers. text: Okay okay I hear what everyone's saying, but 0:35 WE ALL DEAL WITH IT, LADIES. No matter how we look - this can be about our abilities, any weaknesses we have, not just our bodies. If you read the plot of the story, you find out that in the end, she LEARNS that the way she views herself and her confidence are the one of the most important things about a person. That's the reason she does so well, and why people are so impressed. It's her optimism, her spunkiness, her willing to take risks that make everyone admire her so much. Not her body, regardless of whether she is pretty or ugly. I know I have a pretty face and all-right talents, but it's my confidence and boldness that will get me a job, get me through college and change things for the better in my life. So stop thinking this movie is about "labeling" a woman with a rather healthy weight fat and start looking at what's valuable about it.

text: This movie is actually seems to be soooooo relatable. Despite society as a whole (lets exclude youtube comments*) engaging in the body positivity movement, it is still a message told to all overweight people every day that to truly be 'attractive', you need to be skinny. THAT is what the movie is highlighting. People are jumping aboard the body positivity train to be politically correct but aren't changing their perceptions of what is beautiful/attractive, and it's important to highlight before this becomes even more of a thing that is (primarily*) silently known universally.  *There is still a lot of hate out there for overweight people. Just look at some of the comments on this video. This typically happens on sites such as youtube where people can be pretty much anonymous and post whatever they want and not feel that they personally will be affected.

text: I know from interviews that she compares how she looks to how the people around her look. She thinks she's really plain compared to other "stars." The thing is - maybe it doesn't matter? I think the fact that we compare ourselves at all - that we feel the need to assess and worry about our own and others' attractiveness - reveals we lack imagination and perspective. If you are healthy, and your appearance in and of itself doesn't perceptibly repel people - then I think it's safe, and far more fulfilling, to focus on other things, that make more of a difference to your own and other people's well-being. Take a look around your community and the world, and you will see so many problems that need addressing, that go way beyond feeling like you can wear cute outfits and having a significant other and friends who adore you.

I don't like Trump either (even though I lean right), but I like what he has done for the economy. I don't need to like Trump on a personal level to accept him and support him as the leader of our country. You don't need to like Amy's personal views (no matter how nasty she can get) to accept her role as an entertainer. We are all still humans and as much as you think it reflects on Amy all the hatred she is receiving on this forum, in reality, it's only reflecting on you. text: I don’t care for Amy’s politics, but I think she is beautiful and funny.  I like the social justice premise of the comedy.  Her confidence goes over the top to make a point for the movie, but it is true that more women should have confidence regardless of whether they fit a typically airbrushed and humanly unattainable image currently en vogue.  Over the centuries and continents, the definition of female beauty will always change.  But our confidence should be steadfast.    Others are attracted to confident people, whether Madison Avenue would agree they have the “right” to be confident or not.  Why should women leave it up to the fashion industry (or anybody else) to decide if they are a worthy human or not?  No one was born morbidly obese.  We were all born at a healthy enough weight to be delivered.  If we were worthy humans as babies, why would extra pounds added later suddenly make us subhuman?  If Amy lost 40 pounds ya’ll would be singing her praises.  There are a lot of Shallow Hals (and Shallow Hollys) out there.  Personally I don’t think Amy’s weight is that high.  That could disappear in 2-3 months.  I’m glad she is a little pudgy & relatable.  In real life, despite her real (current) weight, Amy IS this confident character she portrays.  It may be because she was not always pudgy, so she has a vision of her best self in her memory banks, and bases her confidence off of her basic self, not the current extra 40 pounds, which can come & go.  Also her self confidence is based on other factors besides her appearance.  You would HAVE to have a lot of unshakeable confidence to be a stand-up comedian and actress.  She has a lot to be self confident about.  She is talented, smart and hilarious.  This movie will do good.  I hope to see more women having more confidence going forward.  God says we are all worthy.  Oh, but the majority have turned their backs on God — ooops!  Mistake.  Our Creator is where true confidence originates...  PS:  I think it’s awesome how the super thin girls don’t know how to respond when a larger female has more confidence than they do.  PPS:  I find is hypocritical that some of the same ppl who gush online over the beauty of people who have been disfigured or are disabled in some physically obvious way, will turn around and criticize a very beautiful woman for carrying extra weight.  We now know there are multiple reasons people gain weight, and hardly ANY of them have anything to do with diet and exercise.  A very cursory internet search, if one were willing to have their unfair assumptions and prejudices challenged by facts, would quickly outline many of those reasons.

text: Disappointing. Disregarding the fact that Amy is in this, this is not the right message to send girls or women watching this. There’s literally a scene where Amy yells at a skinny girl for having low self esteem just because she’s skinny? Really? That’s not feminism. A better protagonist would see this nearing the climax and realize that all women, even skinny women, are affected by beauty standards. Another important thing, the protagonist shouldn’t have to bump her head and rip her hair out just the “see she’s pretty”. A better plot would be if the protagonist creates a social commentary on beauty standards. She would realize that she’s beatiful just the way she is through lessons she observes through events, strangers, and close friends, like finding a skinnier girl crying in the bathroom about low self esteem and social pressure to fit a mold. This movie has potential to be a crafted and eloquent social commentary, but they take steps backwards that ruins the true message of the story.

It's fine to not care about pretty at all, and feel fine without one care in the world about 'pretty'.  The main thing is, don't go around feeling bad.  The only thing I would advise against- is to judge yourself to be attractive to other people.  That's their choice, not yours. This is the criteria of a well fed, and able person to whom people would like to marry, and feel attracted in the pre-industrial era. That era has more objective and grounded and non-random criteria for beauty and attractiveness. Majority of people  wouldn't find someone with a possible eating disorder (obese or extremely thin) that's evolutionary, natural you do not find an unhealthy person attractive unless there are other extraordinary elements to override this unhealthiness, but this lady  is totally beautiful (face body skin etc), healthy and attractive. Of course there is a level of beauty and attractiveness over this in terms of face and body (minka kelly kind of : ) for example) but this does not refute the beauty of this lady. text: I liked this film a lot despite it being on blast from both sides of american politics. I dislike Amy Schumer and I wasn't expecting much but I saw it because I liked the premise. It is filmed like a disney channel film, often cheesy, pretty much nothing artistic about the lighting, the soundtrack, the best friends trope and hot guy trope and dumb blonde trope etc. But I truly think this film was made to be a rom-com, and that's why I also don't think the feminist criticism of it- that it shouldn't be painted as comedy that heavy woman finds herself attractive- holds any truth here. It wasn't completely filmed as if to mock her, as if she's delusional. It was just that- a romantic comedy. Both style wise and fat-acceptance wise. I liked it. It was strangely inspiring. And I think if there were to be "bad" films like this out there at least they should have a good message like this one. That the power of confidence does not depend on conventional attractiveness.

text: Maintaining a healthy weight should be everyone's goal, regardless of gender. About 40% of the US population is overweight and 1 in 3 are obese. It causes 400,000 deaths per year, and increases healthcare cost by $147 billion. No one should be proud of being overweight or obese, nor should they be devalued for it, but excessive weight is _posing a threat_ to the nation's health. It's a problem we need to take seriously and try to solve.   https://web.archive.org/web/20130510085425/http://www.cdc.gov/obesity/data/adult.html

text: I know a lot of people don't like Amy, but I feel like she was the perfect choice for this movie because of how completely average she looks. She's the type of woman that if you saw her in the street and didn't know who she was you wouldn't notice her, like the majority of people are. I think that's what made her good for this role physically, she's a good representation of the majority of society. It's okay not to be stunning. It's okay to be average (or even below tbh). Don't live your life as less just because you aren't. Take risks, have fun, and enjoy your life because it's the only one you have.

text: Amy Gets a bad rap because... she’s real.  Her stand up is no holds barred and she doesn’t hold back. She’s been criticized so much but just the trailer looks like this movie was made for her. If it were played by someone else, would the public be attacking? No. It’s Amy Shhumer so they criticize.  I can’t wait to see it. If it’s a flop, whatever.  I’ll know she gave the role her all.  Go for it Amy!
